@api_reference
@authentication
>API supports authentication via OAuth2 and API keys.
>Use OAuth2 for user-facing applications.
>Use API keys for server-to-server communication.
:rate_limit=1000/m
@authorization
>Authorization is handled via role-based access control (RBAC).
:_col=permission
:admin=Full access user=Read only service=API access
@configuration
@database
:connection_timeout=30s max_connections=100 retry_policy=exponential backoff
::json
<<<
{"retry": 3, "backoff": "exp"}
>>>
@cache
>application uses Redis for caching to improve performance.
>Cache TTL is 300s
>Cache invalidation is handled automatically
>Session data is not cached because security concerns
@error_handling
>API returns standard HTTP error codes. All errors include JSON body with message field.
>Errors should be logged for debugging purposes. system must handle rate limiting gracefully. Users may retry after specified cooldown period.
@dependencies
>API depends on following services:
>Database (PostgreSQL)
>Cache (Redis)
>Authentication service (OAuth2 provider)
>Notification service (optional)
